function smallestMissingValueSubtree(parents, nums) {
    const n = parents.length;
    const children = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        children.push(new Set());
    }
    for (let i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        children[parents[i]].add(nums[i]);
    }

    const ans = new Array(n);
    dfs(0, parents, nums, children, ans);
    return ans;
}

function dfs(node, parents, nums, children, ans) {
    for (const child of children[node].values()) {
        dfs(child, parents, nums, children, ans);
        children[node].delete(child);
        children[node].add(ans[child]);
    }
    const it = firstLargerOrMissing(children[node], nums[node]);
    ans[node] = (it === nums[node] + 1) ? it - 1 : it;
}

function firstLargerOrMissing(set, target) {
    for (const el of set.values()) {
        if (el > target) return el;
    }
    return target + 1;
}
```

    The algorithm performs a Depth First Search (DFS) on the family tree, using recursion. The DFS function takes in the following parameters: 'node', which is the subtree root, 'parents', 'nums', 'children', and 'ans'. 

We first create a set of children nodes for each node in the tree. We start at the root node and iterate through its children nodes. For each child node, we call the DFS function recursively. Here, we remove the child node from the set of children nodes and insert the value of ans[child] as a new child node.

Then, we find the smallest higher value in the children set that is larger than the subtree root value (nums[node]). We calculate the smallest missing value by subtracting 1 from that found value or adding 1 to the root value if the found value equals to the root value plus one.

After the DFS is completed, we return the ans array. The ans array contains the smallest missing value for each subtree rooted at node i.

